<Base title="Learn the Material — Augmented Engineering">
  <PatternPage number="1" title="Learn the Material" subtitle="LLMs have behavioral properties. Some are permanent. Some are being fixed. Know the difference." advisory={true}>

    <p>Every engineering substrate has properties you design around. You don't ask steel to resist fatigue — you design joints that accommodate it. LLMs are no different.</p>

    <p>The trick: some properties are likely permanent (tied to how LLMs fundamentally work), and some are current limitations being actively fixed. Your workarounds should match.</p>

    <div class="illustration-wrap">
      <IllustrationMaterial />
    </div>

    <h2>The Properties</h2>

    <p><strong>Confident but wrong</strong> (likely permanent). LLMs default to assertive language — "demonstrates" where "suggests" is warranted. Tied to RLHF training rewards. Fix: enforce a confidence-to-language mapping structurally, don't rely on the model to self-calibrate.</p>

    <p><strong>Can observe, can't score</strong> (likely permanent). An LLM reports <code>has_table=true</code> then scores structure=1. It sees the content but can't translate observations into calibrated numbers. Fix: remove scoring from LLMs — use structural features or classifiers instead.</p>

    <p><strong>Plausible-but-wrong outputs</strong> (improving). Results with correct units, reasonable magnitude, coherent reasoning — that are wrong. Frequency is dropping with each model generation. Fix for now: reproduce, don't assess (Pattern 4).</p>

    <p><strong>Scores regress to the mean</strong> (improving). High-quality work scored low, low-quality work scored high. Frontier reasoning models already do better. Fix for now: separate scoring from LLMs.</p>

    <div class="monday-box">
      <h3>Try This Monday</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Before trusting LLM output, ask: is this the kind of task where "looks right" is enough, or do I need to verify the actual result?</li>
        <li>If your LLM scores or rates things: test on both quality extremes. Check if high-quality inputs get compressed and low-quality inputs get inflated.</li>
        <li>If your LLM writes: check whether the language confidence matches the evidence strength. "Shows" and "demonstrates" should be earned.</li>
        <li>When a task needs both analysis AND calibrated scoring, split them into separate steps.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Where This Comes From</h2>

    <div class="evidence-box">
      <p><strong>Confidence inflation:</strong> In one paper draft, 6 of 22 claims used language more confident than evidence warranted. The fix was structural — a confidence-to-language mapping enforced by the writing process, not better prompting. (agent-ready-papers)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="evidence-box">
      <p><strong>Observation-calibration gap:</strong> Five models (14B-27B parameters) all scored high-quality documents too low and inflated low-quality documents. Unfixable by prompt engineering. Architectural response: remove scoring from LLMs entirely, use embedding + structural features classifier. Recovery: 54.7% &rarr; 93.8% within-1 agreement. (vmodel.eu)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="caveat-box">
      <h3>Honest Limitations</h3>
      <p>The "material properties" framing is an analogy. Physical materials have measurable, reproducible, version-independent properties. LLM behaviors are stochastic, version-dependent, and context-sensitive. The specific observations come from one researcher's practice with 14B-27B parameter models in 2025-2026. Always test your own stack.</p>
    </div>

  </PatternPage>
</Base>
